    • What if I move out one point from data ?
      • Yellow line: low bias, high variance
      • Red line: high bias, low variance

Prediction error of a model

\[y = f(X) + \epsilon\]

  • Suppose we have a training test, \[ \begin{align*} \tau=\{(x_1,y_1),\dots,(x_n,y_n)\} \overset{i.i.d.}{\sim} F \end{align*} \] we tend to fit a model \(\hat{f}\) base on the training set and hope that this model can predict new data point \((x^0, y^0)\) well.
    • This new data point \((x^0, y^0)\) comes from \(F\) and be independent of the training data set \(\tau\).
    • A prespecified loss function \(L(Y, \hat{f}(X))\), e.g.: \(\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\hat{f}(X))^2\)
    • We can define the training error over the training sample \[\bar{err}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^nL(y_i,\hat{f}(x_i))\]
  • for example

ref

For the yellow line, \(\sum_{i=1}^n(y_i-\hat{f}(X))^2=0\)

Prediction error of a model

  • Intuitively, we want to minimize the prediction error against new data \[ \text{Err}_{\tau}=E_{X_0,Y_0}[L(Y^0, \hat{f}(X^0)|\tau] \]
    • we call this conditional expection testing error or generalization error
    • Here the training set \(\tau\) is fixed, and the test error refers to the error for this specific training set.
    • However, its not possible to estimate conditional error, given only the information in the same training set.
  • If we can collect many training data set \(\{\tau_1, \dots,\tau_m\}\), the expected prediction error can be obtained. \[ \text{Err}=E_{\tau}E_{X_0,Y_0}[L(Y^0, \hat{f}(X^0)|\tau] \]
    • Estimation of test error for a particular training set is not easy in general, given just the data from that same training set. Instead, Cross Validation may provide reasonable estimates of expected error Err.

Prediction error of a model

  • Why we need additional testing data ?
    • since training error is not a good estimate of testing error.
  • 100 simulated training set of size 50 each, as the model complexity is increased
    • light blue: training error
    • light red: conditional test error
    • solid blue: expected training error (\(\bar{err}\))
    • solid red: expected test error (\(Err\))

  • U shape of \(Err\)

Cross Validation: Random split

  • \(50\% ~~vs~~ 50\%\) case

  • Pros
    • We now have traning and testing Oh yeah ~
  • Cons
    • highly variable
      • depends on outlier or points with high leverage
    • train on fewer observations
      • overestimate the testing error rate

Cross Validation: LOOCV

  • Pros
    • far less bias, since LOOCV use almost all data as training
    • Special case: linear model \[ CV_{(n)}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n\left( \frac{y_i-\hat{y}_i}{1-h_{ii}} \right)^2 \] where \(\hat{y}=Hy, h_{ii}=\frac{\partial\hat{y}_i}{\partial y_i}=\frac{1}{n}+\frac{(x_i-\bar{x})^2}{\sum_{j=1}^n(x_j-\bar{x})^2}, \frac{1}{n}\leq h_{ii}\leq 1\)
  • Cons
    • Each training are almost identical and thus outputs are highly correlated with each other.
      • Mean of many highly correlated quantities has higher variance than does the mean of many quantities that are not as highly correlated.
    • no randomness
    • computational burden

Cross Validation: K-fold

  • K-fold CV, split randomly or split by order (K=5 in this plot)
  • Pros
    • Overlap between the training sets in each model is smaller, outputs of \(k\) fitted models that are some what less correlated with each other.
  • Cons
    • Computational burden (?)
  • K=5 ? k=10? k=20?

Conditional or Expected test error ?

\[ \text{Err}_{\tau}=E_{X_0,Y_0}[L(Y^0, \hat{f}(X^0)|\tau] \]

\[ \text{Err}=E_{\tau}E_{X_0,Y_0}[L(Y^0, \hat{f}(X^0)|\tau] \]

A common mistake while implementing CV

Consider \(N=50\) in two equal-sized classes, and \(p=5000\) (standard Gaussian) that are independent of the class labels. The true test error rate of any classifier is \(50\%\)

\[ L(Y,\hat{f}(X))=\frac{1}{n}\sum_i I\{Y_i\neq \hat{f}(X_i)\} 100\% \]

  • Approach I
    1. Screen the predictors: find a subset of good predictors that show strong correlation (univariate) with the class labels. (choose first \(100\) predictors)
    2. Using these \(100\) predictors to build a multivariate classifier.
    3. Use CV to estimate the unknown tuning parameters and to estimate the prediction error of the final model.
  • Approach II
    • Divide the samples into \(K\) CV folds at random.
    • for each fold \(k=1,2,\dots,K\)
      1. find a subset of good predictors that show strong correlation (univariate) with the class labels, using all of the samples except those in fold \(k\).
      2. Using these \(100\) predictors to build a multivariate classifier, using all of the samples except those in fold \(k\).
      3. Use the classifier to predict the class labels for the samples in fold \(k\)

A common mistake while implementing CV

Consider \(N=50\) in two equal-sized classes, and \(p=5000\) (standard Gaussian) that are independent of the class labels. The true test error rate of any classifier is \(50\%\)

\[ L(Y,\hat{f}(X))=\frac{1}{n}\sum_i I\{Y_i\neq \hat{f}(X_i)\} 100\% \]

  • Wrong way (avg CV = \(3\%\))
    1. Screen the predictors: find a subset of good predictors that show strong correlation (univariate) with the class labels. (choose first \(100\) predictors)
    2. Using these \(100\) predictors to build a multivariate classifier.
    3. Use CV to estimate the unknown tuning parameters and to estimate the prediction error of the final model.
  • Right way
    • Divide the samples into \(K\) CV folds at random.
    • for each fold \(k=1,2,\dots,K\)
      1. find a subset of good predictors that show strong correlation (univariate) with the class labels, using all of the samples except those in fold \(k\).
      2. Using these \(100\) predictors to build a multivariate classifier, using all of the samples except those in fold \(k\).
      3. Use the classifier to predict the class labels for the samples in fold \(k\)

Bootstrap

  • Training set \(Z=(z_1,z_2,\dots,z_n), z_i=(x_i, y_i)\)
    1. Randomly draw dataset with replacement from the original training set.
    2. Do this \(B\) times to obtain \(B\) bootstrap datasets
    3. Refit the model to each of the bootstrap datasets

  • Q: What is most efficient in MLE theory ?

Maximum Likelihood Theory

  • \(P_{\theta}(x)\) probability density function
  • \(L_x(\theta)\) likelihood function \[ P_{\theta}(x) = L_x(\theta) \] We can find local/global maximum \(\hat{\theta}(X_n)\) that maximize \(L_x(\theta)\)
  • Asymptotic theory of MLE \[ X_1, \dots, X_n ~ \underset{\sim}{{\tiny i.i.d}} ~ P({x;\theta_0}) \] then, with some regular conditions \[ \sqrt{n}(\hat{\theta}(X_n)-\theta_0) \rightarrow N(0, I^{-1}(\theta_0)) \] where \(I(\theta)=-E\left[\frac{\partial^2 l(x;\theta)}{\partial\theta^2}\right]\)
  • Cramer-Rao Lower Bound

The variace of any unbiased estimator \(\tilde{\theta}\) of \(\theta\) is bounded by information. \[ \text{var}(\tilde{\theta})\geq\frac{1}{I(\theta)} \]

  • efficiency of an estimator \[ e(\hat{\theta}) = \frac{I(\theta)^{-1}}{\text{var}(\hat{\theta})} \]
